A square is changed into a pentagon by building an equilateral triangle on top of it, as shown. By what percent does the perimeter increase going from the square to the pentagon?
\begin{center}
    \begin{asy}
    size(6cm);
    defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(unitsquare);

draw((2,1)--(2,0)--(3,0)--(3,1));

draw((3,1)--(2,1),dashed);

draw((2,1)--(2.5,1.8)--(3,1));

draw((1.2,0.5)--(1.8,0.5),Arrow(SimpleHead));
    \end{asy}
\end{center}

}

\textbf{Answer:} Let a side length of the square be $x$. The original perimeter is $4x$. In adding the equilateral triangle, one of the side lengths of the square is eliminated while two congruent side lengths of the triangle are added. Thus, the final perimeter is $5x$. The increase in perimeter is $\frac{5x-4x}{4x}=\boxed{25\
}
